  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE (RISKS) ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is perfect. Here's what a DCF inherently misses for an E&P company like EOG.</p>

  <h3>Downside Risks (Our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commodity Price Volatility:</strong> The biggest risk to any oil and gas producer. If WTI crude or natural gas prices sustain severe declines, cash flows will drop precipitously, rendering our growth estimates obsolete.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Increasing stringency in environmental regulations or restrictions on drilling on federal lands can increase costs or limit future resource extraction.</li>
    <li><strong>Cost Inflation:</strong> Rising costs for oilfield services, steel, and labor could compress margins if not offset by higher realization prices.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Upside Risks (Our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Supply Shocks:</strong> Sustained disruptions in global oil supply could drive crude prices significantly higher, leading to massive short-term cash flow generation that exceeds our conservative baseline.</li>
    <li><strong>Efficiency Gains:</strong> Continued advancements in drilling technologies and well productivity could lower breakeven costs further, increasing free cash flow margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Capital Returns:</strong> EOG's commitment to returning cash to shareholders via special dividends and buybacks could yield higher actual returns to the investor than the static model implies.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While the risk-free rate is around 4.18%, investing in exploration and production companies carries substantial inherent risks, primarily commodity price volatility. A 9% required rate of return balances these sector risks against EOG's premium asset base and historically strong balance sheet.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why assume only 3% growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">EOG prioritizes disciplined capital allocation over maximum production growth. They aim for steady, high-return growth rather than oversupplying the market. A 3% FCF growth assumption is conservative and reflects long-term sustainable operations rather than aggressive short-term scaling.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why focus on Free Cash Flow instead of Earnings?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">In a capital-intensive industry like oil and gas, Earnings (Net Income) include significant non-cash expenses like depreciation, depletion, and amortization (DD&A). Free Cash Flow tells us exactly how much actual cash is left over after maintaining the asset base, which is the true source of value for shareholders.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the underlying assumptions, particularly regarding future commodity prices. Always do your own research.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

